# 06: The Full GPT Model

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:nx, "~> 0.10"},
  {:exla, "~> 0.10"},
  {:emlx, github: "elixir-nx/emlx", branch: "main"},
  {:kino, "~> 0.14"},
  {:vega_lite, "~> 0.1"},
  {:kino_vega_lite, "~> 0.1"}
])

# Backend: "emlx" (default, Apple Metal GPU), "exla", or "emlx_cpu"
backend = System.get_env("NX_BACKEND", "emlx")

case backend do
  "exla" ->
    Nx.global_default_backend(EXLA.Backend)
    Nx.Defn.global_default_options(compiler: EXLA)
    IO.puts("Backend: EXLA (CPU on Mac, CUDA on Linux)")

  "emlx_cpu" ->
    Nx.global_default_backend({EMLX.Backend, device: :cpu})
    Nx.Defn.global_default_options(compiler: EMLX)
    IO.puts("Backend: EMLX (CPU)")

  _ ->
    Nx.global_default_backend({EMLX.Backend, device: :gpu})
    Nx.Defn.global_default_options(compiler: EMLX)
    IO.puts("Backend: EMLX (Apple Metal GPU)")
end

alias VegaLite, as: Vl
```

## The Complete Architecture

Over the last five notebooks, we've built every component of a GPT model individually. Now we assemble them into the full model. Here's the complete data flow:

```
token IDs → token embedding + position embedding → dropout
  → transformer block 1
  → transformer block 2
  → ...
  → transformer block N
  → final LayerNorm
  → lm_head (project to vocabulary) → logits
```

The input is a batch of token ID sequences. The output is **logits** -- a score for every possible next token at every position. Higher logit = the model thinks that token is more likely to come next.

